Thank you for your kind words, Tom. I expect
you to follow up on them by pointing out, on a
line-by-line basis, how I have gone completely
wrong in this exegesis -- how the meanings I find
clash hopelessly with the sense and tone of its
words. I expect you to demonstrate how the
meanings found by Stratfordian commentators
are manifestly superior in each case.

1. O thou my lovely Boy who in thy power,
2. Dost hold Time's fickle glass, his sickle, hour;
3. Who hast by waning grown, and therein showest,
4. Thy lovers withering, as thy sweet self growest.
5. If Nature (sovereign mistress over wrack)
6. As thou goest onwards still will pluck thee back,
7. She keeps thee to this purpose, that her skill
8. May time disgrace, and wretched minute kill.
9. Yet fear her O thou minion of her pleasure,
10. She may detain, but not still keep her treasure!
11. Her *Audit* (though delayed) answered must be,
12. And her *Quietus* is to render thee.

This sonnet has given rise to much puzzlement
-- much of which is unexpressed. Commentators
silently let lines and phrases slip by, not attempting
to elucidate their meanings. They may discuss
particular words -- but they avoid looking at possible
meaning of lines as a whole. This, of course, is a
common pattern in all 'exegeses' of Shakespeare
sonnets but is more blatant than usual here.

Commentators suggest that it is addressed to the
'fair youth', but that leads to much that is mystifying.
How does the 'fair youth' hold &quot;Time's fickle glass&quot;?
How can he have this strange relationship with
Nature? What does he have to fear from her (in
line 9)? And what does the 'Audit' have to with him?
Or how can 'Nature' render him?

Nothing in the tone of the words fits any scenario
conceivable within the Stratfordian framework --
nor the Baconian, nor Marlite nor any other --
except for that which you are about to see.

I have argued before that the addressee is the
Cupid-like figure of figure of Time -- the infant boy
who holds the hour-glass of Time, and who
commonly represents the start of a period, usually
a year. (Such a figure is one of the two shown on
the top of the Stratman's memorial.) However, that
can only be a part of an explanation -- a superficial
tone, or an excuse of a theme. This poet did not
address banal sonnets to abstract figures. He
always had things to say, and it was invariably
pointed.

Bookburn's commentator remarks on the opening
phrase: &quot;Some commentators have objected to this
phrase and found it too mawkish&quot;. And, indeed it is.
It is almost explicitly sarcastic.

The sonnet is unusual in not being addressed to
his love -- but to 'my lovely Boy'. Possibly it is a
misreading of this sonnet, more than any other,
that has given rise to the fantastic notion of the
'Fair Youth'. Absurd misreadings of that nature
were probably inevitable, given the extent of
Stratfordian misconceptions. Unlike all other
sonnets, the tone here is one of shameless
disparagement of its addressee.

It probably originated in the competition between
Oxford and Ralegh, as each submitted verses to
their 'adored' as part of the courtly exchange in
seeking her love -- a game that she enjoyed
beyond measure.

Most of Ralegh's poems have been lost, but one:
&quot;Nature, that washed her hands in milk&quot; has
echoes of Sonnet 126. In these verses, 'Nature'
is the Queen, despising Time.

But Time, which Nature doth despise,
And rudely gives her love the lie,
Makes hope a fool and sorrow wise,
His hands do neither wash, nor dry,
But being made of steel and rust,
Turns snow and silk and milk to dust.

The light, the belly, lips, and breath
He dims, discovers, and destroys;
With those he feeds, but fills not, Death,
Which sometimes were the food of joys;
Yea, Time doth dull each lively wit,
And dries all wantonness with it.

The tone of Sonnet 126 is sarcastic, with the
poet's target being Ralegh sometime after mid-
1581 when he became the new favourite.

1. O thou my lovely Boy who in thy power,

'Boy' had a strongly derogatory sense (shown as
obsolete in the OED -- sense 4):
CORIOLANUS (v.v.101 see also 104 and 117)
Measureless liar, thou hast made my heart
Too great for what contains it. Boy! O slave!

'Boy' was also the standard spelling for 'buoy'.
'Boy' and 'buoy' are (and were ) pronounced
identically in the U.K. and in all navies. Oxford
regarded Ralegh as a lower-class servant or
knave, and little better than flotsam.

The 'lovely' part of the description is a sarcastic
reference to his good looks -- and possibly to
the Queen's regard or description of him.

2. Dost hold Time's fickle glass, his sickle, hower;

This line is ostensibly addressed to the Cupid-
like figure of time, holding the hour-glass, which
over the year (or other period) turns into a sickle.
That should strictly be a scythe; the poet
substitutes 'sickle' as a play on 'fickle' ('s' and 'f'
were almost identical in Elizabethan script) and
as a hint at the moon (with its waning and
growing).

Note the correct punctuation of the Quarto, with a
comma before 'hower' (an old spelling of 'whore').
(Modern editors routinely change the punctuation
here, pretending to have some better insight into
the poet's meaning.) The poet calls Ralegh 'a
whore', picturing him as holding a 'fickle' mirror for
the Queen. When she looks at him, she sees a
reflection of herself as a young girl in her twenties.
This, the poet suggests, is sick. The 'fickleness'
is primarily in the Queen -- she may drop her
favourite at any moment, as she has recently
dropped the poet.

3. Who hast by waning grown, and therein showest,

Again this is nicely contrived to be apparently
about the figure of Time, and his hour-glass,
whereas the sharpness of its point is directed
at Ralegh. 'Wane' as a noun (OED sb1) had
several meanings now obsolete: 1 = 'want, lack
shortage'; b = 'lack, fault, defect'; c = 'omission,
shortening'; 2 = 'need, want, poverty' . . .

Ralegh, by constantly begging to his mistress,
and by pointing out his poverty had grown in
wealth.

&quot;While his ships were away, Ralegh continued to rise in the
Queen's favour. He was a persistent petitioner, for himself
and for his friends and clients. 'When, Sir Walter,' the Queen
asked, 'will you cease to be a beggar?' 'When your gracious
Majesty ceases to be a benefactor,' he replied. . . &quot;
(*Ralegh*, by John Winton, page 54)

4. Thy lovers withering, as thy sweet self growest.

As Ralegh grew in favour and wealth, he became
extremely unpopular ('thy lovers withering').

&quot;Few others shared Elizabeth's high opinion of Ralegh, for
most people had a violent aversion to him. He was &quot;commonly
noted for using of bitter scoffs and reproachful taunts&quot; in
everyday social intercourse, and his biting and sarcastic tongue
&quot;bred him much dislike&quot; . . Far from being disturbed by his
unpopularity Ralegh positively exulted in it, but though Elizabeth
did not mind that he showed no interest in courting the public,
she was less happy about the fact that he sometimes seemed
to go out of his way to cause gratuitous offence. He was the sort
of man who would &quot;lose a friend to coin a jest&quot; . . &quot;
(*Elizabeth*, Anne Somerset, page 337)

As a further sense, Ralegh was noted for his
capacity for a 'withering' comment.

4. . . . . as thy sweet self growest.

A bitterly sarcastic comment.

5. If Nature (sovereign mistress over wrack)

Superficially, the poet is speaking of a god-like
figure of 'Nature' which seeks to hold back the
progress of Time. In reality he is talking about their
joint 'sovereign mistress'. The 'wrack' here was
the wreck of the state, as she disdained marriage,
refusing to breed an heir, virtually guaranteeing (in
the poet's view) civil war on, or before, her death.
'Wrack' is a also a marine reference -- to the wrecks
and to the worthless seaweed littering the shore --
with the clear implications, firstly, that Ralegh is
largely responsible for that 'wreck' and, secondly,
is no better than the worthless sea-weed.

6. As thou goest onwards still will pluck thee back,

Whenever her close favourites wanted to take
charge of some enterprise which involved leaving
the court, the Queen usually forbade their departure.
Ralegh would have loved to go to Virginia to see
that his colonies started on the right basis, but the
Queen would not allow it. Occasionally they left
court, but were then usually ordered to return.

The poet is also referring to Ralegh's wider political
prospects. Walter was intensely ambitious, and had
much ability, but the poet could see that he would
never achieve high office. The Queen would always
'hold him back'.

7. She keeps thee to this purpose, that her skill

While still apparently writing within the framework
of the gods of Nature and Time, the poet becomes
almost blunt in stating his views on the manner in
which the court is run. He detests the way in which
the Queen is now behaving. She should be seizing
the last possible opportunity to marry and have an
heir. She refuses to do that, instead wasting her
time on this worthless knave. The poet tells him
that she keeps him solely to pass the time in
frivolity.

8. May Time disgrace, and wretched minute kill.

She will disgrace her time, both by remaining
barren, and by carrying on with this unpopular
scoundrel. He is kept to help her kill time.

