In order to maintain the abstract level of reading, I think
it's logical to capitalize the personifications of Boy,
Time, Nature, but not &quot;quietus.&quot; Death is represented in
the &quot;quietus,&quot; but not named as antagonist to Love? This
would emphasize Boy as Cupid, suggesting &quot;thy lovers&quot; as all
people in love, but alluding to addressee, as well. In this
we can see the image of the moon &quot;waning&quot; (becoming pale and
sickly) as love grows (groans), being pale and groaning
characteristic of the convention; and perhaps a buried image
of planting by night. I agree that &quot;minion of her pleasure&quot;
would not refer to Cupid, though.

On the whole, my impression is that S follows the derivative
convention of using classical personifications of abstract
ideas yet shows greater insight involving subtle nuances of
their interactions. I see some suggestion that Nature, who
&quot;may detain, but not still keep, her treasure,&quot; also
represents something of Love and perhaps a distracting SO.

