1. O thou my lovely Boy who in thy power,
2. Dost hold Time's fickle glass, his sickle, hower;
3. Who hast by waning grown, and therein showest,
4. Thy lovers withering, as thy sweet self growest.
5. If Nature (sovereign mistress over wrack)
6. As thou goest onwards still will pluck thee back,
7. She keeps thee to this purpose, that her skill
8. May time disgrace, and wretched minute kill.
9. Yet fear her O thou minion of her pleasure,
10. She may detain, but not still keep her treasure!
11. Her *Audit* (though delayed) answered must be,
12. And her *Quietus* is to render thee.

To you, my lovely Boy, who [seemingly] have the power,
to stop Time's hourglass, and make his sickle HOVER
[hover = be suspended in air, not descending]

[&quot;sickle&quot; is the correct word here, by the way. A sickle is a
one-hand tool: Time carries the glass in one hand, the sickle in the
other. If it were a scythe, which is a two-hand tool, Time could not
also carry the glass.]

Who has by aging grown [in beauty], and thereby show,
Thy lover's withering [in beauty by comparison], as they sweet self
growest. [more beautiful]

If Nature (sovereign mistress over destruction)
As you go onward [toward decay] still will pull you back,

She keeps thee to this purpose, that her skill
May time disgrace, and wretched minute kill.

[The disgracing of time means the dethroning of time: time is not
royal here, but having been dethroned becomes common, thus &quot;time&quot; gets
no capitalization. Nature is using the lovely boy for her own
purpose, to show her sovereignty over common time and his wretched
minutes.]

Yet fear her O thou minion of her pleasure,
She may detain, but not still keep her treasure!

[A warning to the boy, since the seeming power he has, that was first
mentioned, is not truly his own. He is Nature's favorite, for now,
but she will not hold him forever.]

Her _Audit_ (though delayed) answered must be,
And her _Quietus_ is to render thee.

[An audit is a hearing. The quietus, then, is when speech is
finished. After all has been said, the boy will be rendered, handed
over, to common time.]

There are no lines missing, probably. First, it is not a sonnet.
Second, &quot;quietus&quot; means an end to speech, an end of the &quot;hearing.&quot;
Third, to render is to hand over.

The closing lines are a reminder of the whole exercise. The sonnets
to the lovely boy have been an audit, a hearing, in which the poet has
pled his case. Now we have reached the quietus, following the
hearing, speech is finished, and the boy is handed over to common
time. As it stands the poem is, and has, a proper end to the sequence
of sonnets to the boy.

