1. O thou my lovely Boy who in thy power,
2. Dost hold Time's fickle glass, his sickle, hover;
3. Who hast by waning grown, and therein shovest,
4. Thy lovers withering, as thy sweet self growest.

To you, my lovely Boy, who [seemingly] have the power,
To stop Time's inconstant hourglass, and make his sickle hover
[without descending];
Who have by waning [becoming less of a boy] grown, and therein
shovest,
[shove others aside, as new fruit shoves aside older withering fruit]
Thy lovers withering, as thy sweet self growest.

The use of &quot;hover&quot; and &quot;shovest&quot; in lines 2 and 3 respectively gives a
reading that has meaning.

It also gives a sort of abba rhyme, which is interesting. &quot;Rhyme&quot; is
not correct, the proper word escapes me. It gives a visual pattern of
abba for the -w- and -v-. Of course the -er- and -est- endings go
aabb.

In the use of &quot;shovest&quot; there is no implication whatever of the boy
being &quot;pushy&quot; as a defect of character. It's a natural process that
the new growing fruit pushes forward into the sun, as the old fruit
withers, recedes, and soon drops.

I find that &quot;hover&quot; and &quot;shovest&quot; give an interesting, sensible
reading. Millions may disagree.

The poem has remarkable depth. For whom does the boy have power to
stop the hourglass? The poet, for one. As the poet's thoughts turn
to the boy, while he writes, he does not feel the passing of common
minutes. The poet &quot;hands over&quot; the boy with considerable regret. The
poem speaks of the boy, nature, and the poet himself. It's very fine.

