The poem is not merely about appearances. For one thing, the effects
of time are real - growth, withering - and are stated as such. The
poem speaks of reality, loud and clear. The poem is about the reality
behind the appearance, and it is couched in terms of educating a naive
recipient to the facts of life. &quot;Dear Boy, this is thy fate&quot; the poem
says.

I do observe, you did not say the poem was _only_ about appearances.
My remarks here are probably not an argument with you.

New generations do take over the territory of the old. And if -
musing here - this series of poems to the boy were an attempt to
persuade the boy to marry the poet's daughter, the inheritance of
territory would be manifest. Again, be that as it may.

Plants are unquestionably very competitive, and one will shove another
powerfully, as any gardener has seen. The &quot;shoving&quot; of plants will
break concrete. This &quot;shoving&quot; is one reason weeds are a problem in a
garden, also why gardeners thin seedlings. Weeds will not only shade
desired plants, but crowd (shove) them, deprive them of water and
nourishment so they wither, and even kill them, all quite naturally.

More to the point, &quot;sweet self&quot; indicates fruit; many vegetables are
sweet, but the term is more often applied to fruit. For fruit on an
everbearing plant, such as some strawberries, the phenomenon can be
observed directly, of new fruit growing and pushing aside older,
withering fruit in the same cluster.

But the botanical metaphor I invoke could be confined to line 4 with
no difficulty. It's easy to read too much into a poem, as you are
undoubtedly aware.

Do you find &quot;sickle hour&quot; acceptable? I ask because &quot;hover&quot; and
&quot;shov'st&quot; would match in the letter -v-, although admittedly disrupt
the strict rhyme pattern.

