2. Dost hold Time's fickle glass, his sickle, hower;
[To restrain Time's hourglass (which is fickle in favoring first one,
then another), and likewise restrain Time's sickle, delaying the hour
when it descends.]

&quot;Hour&quot; will work. I could accept it. I don't particularly like it,
but that's beside the point. The verse is so abbreviated it allows
the reader a lot, or demands a lot.

The passage of time, represented by Time's glass, is fickle, in that
where earlier it had favored the poet, as he grew into his prime, the
passing of time now disfavors the poet and favors the boy instead. As
