The reasons here are obvious, even if missed by all
the idiot Stratfordian commentators, who put it down
to careless compositors.

Rhyming is a difficult topic because we do not know
how words were pronounced at the time. We can
only guess at 'bad rhymes' -- as in the &quot; . . shov'st /
grow'st &quot; one of this sonnet, where the general opinion
is that it is bad. However, the poet seems to go into
distinctly bad verse when he's having a special go at
Ralegh's versifying. See Sonnet 56, for example, 3rd
quatrain. 'Ocean' was Walter's posy, adopted by him
in his own poetry to the Queen.

9. Let this sad *Intrim* like the Ocean be
10. Which parts the shore,where two contracted new,
11. Come daily to the banks,that when they see
12. Return of love,more blest may be the view.

There are other instances where I am sure the
poet is imitating Ralegh's 'bad verse'. Ralegh
was addicted to staccato-like monosyllabic verse,
and our poet parodies it on occasion.

