There is more. They look at how English speakers spell foreign words.
They look at how foreigners spell English words. They watch for trends;
as a general rule, changes in pronunciation follow unbreakable rules.
The rules change from language to language, from place to place, and
from century to century, but in a given place, at a given time, in a
given language, the changes are always consistent; if they appear not to
be, there always turns out to be another rule that impinges on the first.

Back in the days when being an English major actually meant something,
all this was required learning.

So, while reconstructed antique pronunciations must always be regarded
as somewhat conjectural and tentative, they're surprisingly solid.

