There are various general sources on linguistics that go into the sound
laws. Or, for a taste of it, look at any Old English textbook.

Remember that before the invention of printing, people generally spelled
as they spoke, and regularized, fixed spelling in English didn't settle
down until the late 17th-early 18th century. Furthermore, a great many
general trends can be tracked by comparing related languages. In
particular, the evolution of Latin into Portuguese, Spanish, Catalan,
French, Langue d'Oc, Sardinian, Italian, Sicilian, Romansh, Romanian,
etc., has been _very_ thoroughly studied, as has been (but usually from
a more bird's-eye view) the evolution of other languages of the
Indo-European family. (Languages of other families generally don't have
a long written history, or are not written phonetically, or, in the
cases of Hebrew and Arabic, have atypical histories due to religious
considerations.) And, of course, where we have evidence from the period
when a language was first being written, and we know where the alphabet
came from (usually Latin), we can bet that the letters were being used
for the old sound, as much as possible. (Old English had the sounds
&quot;th&quot;, &quot;w&quot;, and &quot;a&quot; as in &quot;cat&quot;, which Latin lacked; special letters were
invented for them, though they were later dropped.)

