<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; So how do you read &quot;solye&quot;? Here's an excellent instance, perhaps, of your
&gt; 'difficilior lectio', which we must strive in some twisted way to understand
&gt; rather than emend. Please explain.

"/>

The Stratfordian misreadings come from the
assumption that the author was publishing a
book of verse designed to be sold to a buying
public -- which it must have been expected to
read and understand without much trouble.
So therefore it was in relatively straightforward
English, and said relatively straightforward things.

The 'solye' example is not one for the 'difficilior
lectio' rule since we do not know what the poet
meant. The rule applies when there are two (or
more) possible readings, but one is more
obscure, unusual or peculiar.

In this case, we do not know what 'soyle' means.
We should leave it at that, and not replace it
with an over-simplistic 'soil' -- which does not,
in fact, make a lot of sense in that context.

Sonnet 69
1. Those parts of thee that the world's eye doth view
2. Want nothing that the thought of hearts can mend:
3. All tongues (the voice of souls) give thee that end,
4. Uttering bare truth even so as foes Commend.
5. Thy outward thus with outward praise is crown'd,
6. But those same tongues that give thee so thine own,
7. In other accents do this praise confound
8. By seeing farther than the eye hath shown.
9. They look into the beauty of thy mind,
10. And that in guess they measure by thy deeds,
11. Then, churls their thoughts (although their eyes were kind)
12. To thy fair flower add the rank smell of weeds,
13. But why thy odour matcheth not thy show,
14. The soyle is this, that thou dost common grow.

